Short answer: no.

Longer answer:
Turn your switch case values into a lookup map or an array, and test the value as it comes in so you can throw an error before it reaches your switch case.

That can be done like this:

```
const arrayOfCases = [&#39;name&#39;, &#39;email&#39;, &#39;city&#39;, &#39;state&#39;, &#39;address&#39;]

if(arrayOfCases.includes(userInput)) {
   // your switch case here
} else {
   // handle invalid data
}
```

